üöÄ StorageOS Pro: Setup Guide
StorageOS Pro is a high-performance disk monitoring and cleanup utility that runs as a standalone desktop application with root-level deletion capabilities.

üìã Prerequisites
The target machine must be running a Linux distribution with a Desktop Environment (Ubuntu, Mint, Debian, etc.).

1. Install System GUI Dependencies
Before touching Python, the system needs the GTK and WebKit libraries to render the application window:

Bash

sudo apt update
sudo apt install -y python3-gi python3-gi-cairo gir1.2-gtk-3.0 gir1.2-webkit2-4.1 libcanberra-gtk-module libcanberra-gtk3-module
Note: If gir1.2-webkit2-4.1 is not found, try gir1.2-webkit2-4.0.

üõ†Ô∏è Environment Setup
2. Clone and Prepare Virtual Environment
To ensure the app can access the system GUI libraries while keeping other dependencies isolated, create a virtual environment with system-site-packages enabled:

Bash

# Create the project directory
mkdir storageos-app && cd storageos-app

# Create a venv that "borrows" system GTK/GI libraries
python3 -m venv --system-site-packages venv
source venv/bin/activate

# Install Python dependencies
pip install pywebview fastapi uvicorn psutil pyinstaller
üèóÔ∏è Building the Application
3. Compile the Binary
Use PyInstaller to bundle the script into a single executable. We must manually include the gi hooks so the binary can "see" the display server:

Bash

pyinstaller --noconsole --onefile \
--hidden-import=gi \
--hidden-import=gi.repository.Gtk \
--hidden-import=gi.repository.WebKit2 \
--collect-all webview \
--name "StorageOS" main.py
The final binary will be generated in the dist/ folder.

üì¶ System Installation (The "Chrome" Experience)
4. Deploy Binary and Icon
Move the files to standard system locations so the app is recognized globally:

Bash

# Move binary
sudo cp dist/StorageOS /usr/local/bin/storageos
sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/storageos

# Setup Icon (Example using a generated SVG)
sudo mkdir -p /usr/share/icons/storageos
# [Insert your storageos.svg file creation here]
5. Create the Desktop Launcher
Create the entry so it appears in the App Menu and requests root permissions via pkexec:

sudo nano /usr/share/applications/storageos.desktop

Paste the following:

Ini, TOML

[Desktop Entry]
Version=1.0
Type=Application
Name=StorageOS Pro
Comment=Monitor and Clean Disk Space
# The complex Exec line bridges the GUI through the root password prompt
Exec=bash -c "xhost +si:localuser:root; pkexec env DISPLAY=:0 XAUTHORITY=/home/$USER/.Xauthority /usr/local/bin/storageos; xhost -si:localuser:root"
Icon=/usr/share/icons/storageos/icon.svg
Terminal=false
Categories=System;Utility;
fields]

üñ•Ô∏è Usage
Open your Application Launcher.

Search for StorageOS Pro.

Enter your password when prompted (required to delete system junk like /var/log).

Click "Explore" to analyze folders or "Delete Permanently" to free up space.

üßπ Uninstallation
To remove the app completely:

Bash

sudo rm /usr/local/bin/storageos
sudo rm /usr/share/applications/storageos.desktop
sudo rm -rf /usr/share/icons/storageos